<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="mode-of-enzyme-action">Mode of Enzyme Action</h2><ul><li><p>Enzymes are <b>globular proteins</b></p></li><li><p>This means their <b>3D shape</b> (as well as the shape of the <b>active site</b> of an enzyme) is determined by the complex tertiary structure of the protein that makes up the enzyme and is therefore <b>highly specific</b></p></li><li><p>Enzymes have a unique <b>active site</b> where <b>specific substrates bind </b>forming an <b>enzyme-substrate complex</b></p></li><li><p>The <b>active site</b> of an enzyme has a <b>specific shape</b> to fit a <b>specific substrate</b></p></li><li><p>Extremes of <b>heat</b> or <b>pH</b> can alter the protein structure and <b>change the shape</b> of the active site, <b>preventing</b> substrate binding – this is called <b>denaturation</b></p></li><li><p>Substrates <b>collide</b> with the enzymes active site and this must happen at the <b>correct orientation and speed</b> in order for a reaction to occur</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Enzyme-substrate complex" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="510" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Enzyme-substrate-complex.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Enzyme-substrate-complex.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The active site of an enzyme has a specific shape to fit a specific substrate (when the substrate binds an enzyme-substrate complex is formed)</b></i></p><h4 id="enzyme-specificity">Enzyme specificity</h4><ul><li><p>The <b>specificity</b> of an enzyme is a result of the <b>complementary nature</b> between the <b>shape</b> of the <b>active site</b> on the enzyme and its <b>substrate</b>(s)</p></li><li><p>Only <b>one specific substrate will fit into one specific active site</b></p></li><li><p>The shape of the active site (and therefore the specificity of the enzyme) is determined by the <b>complex tertiary structure</b> of the <b>protein</b> that makes up the enzyme:</p><ul><li><p>Proteins are formed from chains of amino acids held together by peptide bonds</p></li><li><p>The order of amino acids determines the shape of an enzyme</p></li><li><p>If the order is altered, the resulting three-dimensional shape changes</p></li></ul></li><li><p>If the <b>tertiary structure of the protein is altered</b> in any way, the shape of the <b>active site will change </b>and the substrate will no longer fit the active site</p></li><li><p>This means that an enzyme-substrate complex will not be able to form and the product(s) will not be produced: <b>the enzyme will not be able to carry out its function</b></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Enzyme substrate specificity" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="998" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Enzyme-substrate-specificity.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>An example of enzyme specificity </b></i></p><h4 id="the-lock-and-key-hypothesis">The lock-and-key hypothesis</h4><ul><li><p>In the 1890’s the first model of enzyme activity was described by Emil Fischer:</p><ul><li><p>He suggested that both enzymes and substrates were <b>rigid structures</b> that <b>locked</b> into each other very <b>precisely</b>, much like a key going into a lock</p></li><li><p>This is known as the ‘<b>lock-and-key hypothesis</b>’</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="_Lock and key hypothesis" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1278" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Lock-and-key-hypothesis.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The Lock and Key hypothesis </b></i></p><h4 id="the-induced-fit-hypothesis">The induced-fit hypothesis</h4><ul><li><p>The lock-and-key model was later <b>modified</b> and adapted to our current understanding of enzyme activity, permitted by advances in techniques in the molecular sciences</p></li><li><p>The <b>modified</b> <b>model</b> of enzyme activity (first proposed in 1959) is known as the ‘<b>induced-fit hypothesis</b>’</p></li><li><p>Although it is very similar to the lock and key hypothesis, in this model the enzyme and substrate <b>interact</b> with each other:</p><ul><li><p>The enzyme and its active site (and sometimes the substrate) can <b>change shape</b> slightly as the substrate molecule enters the enzyme</p></li><li><p>These changes in shape are known as <b>conformational changes</b></p></li><li><p>The conformational changes ensure an <b>ideal binding arrangement</b> between the enzyme and substrate is achieved</p></li><li><p>This <b>maximises the ability of the enzyme to catalyse the reaction</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Induced fit hypothesis" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1300" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Induced-fit-hypothesis.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Induced-fit-hypothesis.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The Induced Fit model of enzyme action</b></i></p></div></div></div>